                    <span class="title-text" 
                        style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Collective 
                    thriving and team creativity in college students’ innovation teams: A serial 
                    mediation model</span></h1>
            </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="text-align: left">
                <span style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p id="para0002" 
                            style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 16px; padding: 0px;">
                            College students’ team creativity was positively impacted by collective thriving 
                            in this study. This study strengthens the explanatory power of the 
                            broaden-and-build theory and positive organizational behavior theory on team 
                            creativity and enriches the research on team creativity by elucidating the key 
                            meaning of a collective positive cognitive and emotional state for team 
                            creativity. It also extends previous research on the results of individual-level 
                            thriving.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p id="para0003" 
                            style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 16px; padding: 0px;">
                            In this study, team voice and team mental model were demonstrated to be 
                            mediating factors in the association between collective thriving and college 
                            students’ team creativity. Serial mediation was also found in the above 
                            relationship. Thus, the internal mechanism by which collective thriving affects 
                            team creativity was explained, which not only deepens the internal logic of the 
                            IPO model but also fills the theoretical gap between collective thriving and 
                            team creativity.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p id="para0004" style="box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">
                            This study investigated the association of collective thriving and team 
                            creativity among Chinese innovation teams comprising college students. The 
                            findings have positive implications. Our study offers a theoretical framework 
                            for the management of innovation teams of college students in other countries 
                            and a foundation for studying different cultures and cross-level thriving.</p>
                    </li>
